CLOSTRIDIUM DIFFICILE, CANINE - CANADA (ONTARIO)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 10 May 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Body and Health, 8 May 2006 [edited]
<http://bodyandhealth.canada.com/channel_health_news_details.asp?news_id=9857&news_channel_id=1020&channel_id=1020&rot=11>

Poodle in pet therapy program found to have epidemic strain of
_Clostridium difficile_
-----------------------------------------------
A poodle involved in a hospital visitation program in south-central
Ontario was discovered to be carrying the _Clostridium difficile_
bacterial strain that has caused severe epidemics of the disease in
Quebec, parts of the United States and Britain, a team of Canadian
researchers reports.
While the researchers are unclear how the dog became infected and
whether it passed the bacteria to patients in the unnamed hospitals
and nursing homes it visited, they said the finding suggests
institutions should consider tighter rules for their pet therapy
programs.
"You have to be careful with therapy dogs because they may not be
these nice little bundles of love that are going around," said lead
author Dr. Sandra Lefebvre, a veterinarian and researcher at the
Ontario Veterinary College in Guelph, Ontario.
"They may be carrying something, and you just need to be more
cautious than people are being right now."
The team disclosed their finding in a letter that will be published
in the June 2006 issue of the journal Emerging Infectious Diseases.
Lefebvre discovered the dog was carrying the epidemic strain of
_Clostridium difficile_ during a study in which she screened hospital
therapy dogs for a variety of human disease agents to see whether
they were picking up or spreading bugs in the facilities they
visited. The dogs were tested for pathogens like
methicillin-resistant _Staphylococcus aureus_ and _C. difficile_.
The toy poodle, which visited hospitals and long-term care facilities
on a weekly basis, was not evidently ill. But it was shedding _C.
difficile_ bacteria.
Testing revealed the bacteria matched the so called epidemic strain
that has triggered large outbreaks of severe and recurrent _C.
difficile_-associated disease in parts of the U.S., Britain and
Canada. This strain, which produces high levels of toxins, is
associated with a high death rate.
Lefebvre, who specializes in companion animal-related zoonoses
(animal diseases that can pass to humans), would not identify the
facilities the dog visits.
There is no firm proof the dog infected any patients, said Lefebvre,
who said the facilities involved were reluctant to share information
with her.
"The most I could get out of them was that you know, they did have an
increase in cases around the time that the dog was tested, so we
could kind of make that link. But I have no idea whether the dog was
the Typhoid Mary or not."
Experts said it was too soon to say whether therapy animals were
spreading _C. difficile_ or were victims that were being put at risk
because of their exposure to sick humans.
"It is of interest, and I think it's something we've got to keep on
the radar screen," said Dr. Clifford McDonald, a physician scientist
at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control who is a leading researcher
on _C. difficile_.
"I don't think we have to stop all pet therapy."
However, therapy animal programs could use tighter controls to ensure
that both patients and health-care workers understand that dogs and
cats can pick up and potentially spread disease agents in their
travels, the authors said.
"There are some proven benefits to these programs," said Dr. Scott
Weese, senior author on the paper. "But it looks like there are risks
too. It's like anything in life, there's a cost-benefit to it. And
it's a matter of managing programs to decrease that cost and maximize
the benefit."
For a related study, Lefebvre has been following therapy animals on
their visits to hospitals. On several occasions she's seen animal
handlers being urged to bring the pets to visit patients who are in
isolation because they have some contagious bug, like MRSA or _C.
difficile_.
Rooms that are off-limits to human visitors probably ought to be
off-limits to 4-legged ones too, the CDC's McDonald suggested.
Lefebvre also thinks health-care workers and patients should be urged
to clean their hands before and after touching therapy animals.
"There's a little more intimacy between the dogs and the patients in
some circumstances. So if they are carrying something, then probably
the chance is a little higher that they would contact it," she said.
[Byline Helen Branswell]
--
