<promed@promedmail.org>
[An excellent review of this organism can be found in ProMED-mail
post 20051202.3472.
_Clostridium difficile_, a gram positive anaerobic bacteria, may be
part of a normal intestinal flora. _C. difficile_ is a major cause of
pseudomembranous colitis and antibiotic associated diarrhea. When the
normal intestinal flora is altered by antibiotics or other disease
processes, the _C. difficile_ flourishes and produces 2 toxins, toxin
A and toxin B, causing a foul-smelling, watery diarrhea.
Toxin A is an enterotoxin, while Toxin B is a cytotoxin.
Demonstration of the toxin in fecal sample is usually required for
definitive diagnosis. This spore forming bacteria can be spread
between patients and through environmental contamination. Frequent
hand washing decreases the spread of this bacteria.
Dogs normally carry this bacteria in their intestine, much the same
as human beings. Likewise, it may express itself when faced with
similar stresses to the normal gut flora. In one study, as many as 50
percent of the dogs carried the bacteria. However, not all the dogs
possessed the toxic strains, and dogs possessing the bacteria were
not all shedding the organism.
The animal in this article appears to have been shedding the
organism, which may serve as notice that hand washing and personal
hygiene are necessary for both the patient being visited and for the
handler. - Mod.TG]
[What is new about this posting is the recognition of the toxinotype
III, ribotype 027 strain of _C. difficile_ in a dog. Finding _C.
difficile_ in the stools of animals has been described by Lefebvre's
Guelph group and others before.
In 2005, Arroyo, et al (1) cite prevalence rates of _C. difficile_ in
the stools of dogs and cats at 6 to 40 percent, and in horses, the
carriage rate was 2 to 29 percent. Arroyo's study reported on 92
strains of the organism isolated from canine stool, 21 from equines
and 20 from humans. They found that 69 percent of canine isolates
were toxin producers, and some strains were indistinguishable between
the species.
In a more recent report screening visitation dogs for potential human
pathogens, Lefebvre (2) found _C. difficile_ in 58 of 102 dogs, and
41 of these (71 percent) were toxigenic.
Whether _C. difficile_, however, can be a zoonotic infection is not
clear. Humans may function as a reservoir for dogs; dogs may function
as a reservoir for humans, or both may be acquiring the potential
pathogen from other animate or inanimate sources.
1. Arroyo LG, Kruth SA, Willey B, et al: PCR ribotyping of
_Clostridium difficile_ isolates originating from human and animal
sources. J Med Microbiol 2005; 54:163-66.
2. Lefebvre SL, Waltner-Toews D, Peregrine AS, et al: Prevalence of
zoonotic agents in dogs visiting hospitalized people in Ontario:
implications for infection control. J Hosp Infect 2006; 62:458-66. -
Mod.LL]
